  "prompt": "How can you convert heat energy directly into electricity?",
  "response": "There are several methods to convert heat energy directly into electricity:\n\n1. Thermoelectric Generator (TEG)\n- Uses Seebeck effect\n- Uses temperature differences to generate electricity\n- Semiconductor materials convert heat directly to electric current\n- Commonly used in small-scale applications\n\n2. Thermionic Conversion\n- Converts heat directly into electricity using electron emission\n- Uses heated electrodes to generate electrical current\n- Potential for high-efficiency energy conversion\n\n3. Thermophotovoltaic (TPV) Cells\n- Similar to solar photovoltaic cells\n- Uses heat-emitting materials to generate light\n- Photovoltaic cells convert this light into electricity\n\n4. Piezoelectric Materials\n- Some materials generate electrical charge when heated\n- Temperature changes create electrical potential\n\n5. Fuel Cells\n- Converts chemical energy from fuel into electricity\n- Uses heat as part of the conversion process\n\n6. Magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) Generators\n- Uses conducting fluid heated to high temperatures\n- Passes fluid through magnetic field to generate electricity\n- Primarily used in large-scale power generation\n\nEach method has different efficiency levels and is suitable for specific applications depending on temperature range, scale, and desired output.",
